{"title_page": "Abduwali Muse", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Abduwali Muse\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name       = Abduwali Muse\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1990}}<ref name=\"BOP\" />\n| birth_place        = [[Galkayo]], [[Somalia]]\n| alias              = Abdulwali Abdukhad Muse,<ref name=\"BOP\" /> Abdul Wali Muse, Wal-i-Musi\n| allegiance         = \n| motive             = \n| charge             = [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|''Maersk Alabama'' hijacking]]\n| conviction         = \n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated on [[piracy]] charges. Sentenced to 33 years and 9 months imprisonment. Currently located at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Edgefield]], to be released April 13, 2038.\n| occupation      = Pirate\n| parents            = Adar Abdurahman Hassan\n}}\n'''Abduwali Muse''' ({{lang-so|Cabdiweli Cabdiqaadir Muuse}}; {{IPA-so|\u0295\u0251bd\u026aw\u025bli \u0295\u0251bd\u026aq\u0251\u02d0d\u026ar mu\u02d0s\u025b|pron}}; {{Audio|En-us-Abdiwali Abdukhadir Muse from Somalia pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg|English pronunciation}}) is a convicted [[Somali people|Somali]] [[pirate]]. He is the sole survivor of four pirates who [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|hijacked]] the {{ship|MV|Maersk Alabama}} in April 2009 and then held Captain [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|Richard Phillips]] for ransom.<ref name=NYDailyNews>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/04/17/2009-04-17_free_and_frisky_sailor_william_rios_held_by_somali_pirates_rejoins_wife_in_harle.html| quote=It was not known when he will be brought to stand trial in New York, chosen because the local FBI office has a history of handling cases in Africa involving major crimes against Americans. His tribe is the Hawiye in the Darood clan. The suspect, believed to be 17 to 19 years old, could face life in prison if convicted.| title=Free and frisky: Maersk Alabama sailor William Rios, held by Somali pirates, rejoins wife in Harlem| date=17 April 2009|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nydailynews.com%2Fnews%2F2009%2F04%2F17%2F2009-04-17_free_and_frisky_sailor_william_rios_held_by_somali_pirates_rejoins_wife_in_harle.html&date=2009-04-20|archivedate=20 April 2009| first1=Erica| last1=Pearson}}</ref> On 16 February 2011, Muse was sentenced to over 33 years in U.S. federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Somali pirate gets over 33 years in prison |first=Tom |last=Hays |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110216/ap_on_re_us/us_piracy_suspect |agency=AAP |date=16 February 2011 |publisher=News.Yahoo.com |accessdate=30 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218083517/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110216/ap_on_re_us/us_piracy_suspect |archivedate=18 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMuse was born in [[Galkayo]], a [[divided city]] in [[Somalia]]. The US Federal Bureau of Prisons states he was born in 1990,<ref name=\"BOP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=70636-054 |title=Inmate Locator |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] |accessdate=22 February 2014 | quote = ABDULWALI ABDUKHAD MUSE, AGE: 24, Register Number: 70636-054}}</ref> while his mother states he was born in 1992,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pirate mother's Obama mercy plea |journal=BBC |date=20 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8008835.stm |accessdate=20 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421011850/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8008835.stm |archivedate=21 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/somalian-pirate-suspect-arrives-in-new-york-to-be-tried-in-u-s-court-1.777441 | title=Somali pirate being flown to New York to be tried in U.S. federal court| date=20 April 2009| publisher=[[CBC News]]| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fworld%2Fstory%2F2009%2F04%2F20%2Fus-somaliapirate.html&date=2009-04-20| archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref> and his father states he was born in 1993.<ref name=\"NbcNews2009-04-20\">{{cite news| url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Captured-Somali-Pirate-En-Route-to-NY-for-Trial.html| title=Captured Somali Pirate Due in NY Court Tomorrow| date=20 April 2009| author=Jonathon Dienst, Victoria Cavaliere| publisher=[[NBC News]]\n|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nbcnewyork.com%2Fnews%2Flocal%2FCaptured-Somali-Pirate-En-Route-to-NY-for-Trial.html&date=2009-04-20| archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/nyregion/22pirate.html| title=Pirate Suspect Charged as Adult in New York| date=21 April 2009| author=Benjamin Weiser|work=[[The New York Times]]| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002203050/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/nyregion/22pirate.html| url-status=live| archivedate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html\n|title=Somali Charged With Piracy in Attack on U.S. Ship| date=22 April 2009| first1=Colleen | last1=Long | first2=Larry | last2=Neumeister|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114044624/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html| url-status=live\n|archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe grew up in poverty often without food or clothes. At a young age he was kicked in the face by a camel and lost two of his front teeth. By the age of 12, he was living alone and initially worked as an assistant to taxi drivers before working as a cook for fishermen. He was married in 2008 but could not afford to establish a home for himself and his wife.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-15068088 |title = Somali pirates face hard time in US prison|work = BBC News|date = 3 October 2011|last1 = Nasaw|first1 = Daniel}}</ref>\n\nAt a hearing to determine Muse's age, Assistant [[United States Attorney]] Brendan McGuire said to U.S. Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck, that Muse had told Americans he was variously 16, 18, 19 and 26 years old.\n\nMuse is short in stature&mdash;Colleen Long and Larry Neumeister, writing for the [[Associated Press]], reported that Muse was, \"only five foot two inches (157&nbsp;cm) tall.\"<ref name=\"AssociatedPress2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5izUbtx1o15cqD9GcYDcuI16mUxQQD97N62H00| title=Pirate comes to NY, world away from home in Africa| date=21 April 2009| author=Colleen Long, Larry Neumeister\n |agency=Associated Press| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Fhostednews%2Fap%2Farticle%2FALeqM5izUbtx1o15cqD9GcYDcuI16mUxQQD97N62H00&date=2009-04-22| archivedate=22 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Attack on the ''Maersk Alabama''==\n{{further|Maersk Alabama hijacking}}\nAccording to his indictment, Muse was the first of the four men who boarded the ''[[Maersk Alabama]]''. During the attack, he was stabbed in the hand by a sailor. The crew attacked and held Muse hostage while [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|Richard Phillips]] offered him and the pirates money to leave the ''Alabama'' safely on the ship's lifeboat. However Muse's fellow pirates forced Phillips into the lifeboat before the ''Alabama'' crew could release Muse. All four pirates escaped the ship, with Phillips held hostage inside the lifeboat. A day later the ''[[USS Bainbridge (DDG-96)|USS Bainbridge]]'' intercepted the lifeboat and navy officers negotiated with the armed pirates for hours and agreed to take Muse on board the ''Bainbridge'' to \"meet\" with elders from his clan to negotiate the release of Phillips. After Muse had been taken on board, the three remaining pirates were shot dead simultaneously before Muse was charged and taken into American custody. Muse was thought to be the first person to be charged with [[piracy]] in an American court in more than 100 years,<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|first=Ed |last=Pilkington |title=Somali teen faces first US piracy charges in over a century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/21/somali-pirate-trial-new-york |work=The Guardian |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2009 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424055601/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/21/somali-pirate-trial-new-york |archivedate=24 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> when courts ruled in 1885 that the [[Ambrose Light (ship)|''Ambrose Light'']] was not a pirate vessel. A more recent case, 2008's ''[[United States v. Shi]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=United States v. Shi |url=http://www.dailycasereport.com/index.php?q=open_pdf/3596 |accessdate=25 April 2009}}</ref> which was quoted in his indictment, involves murder and a crew member taking over a ship and holding a hostage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ellis |first=Steven M. | title= Ninth Circuit Court Upholds Chinese Man's Piracy Conviction | url= http://www.metnews.com/articles/2008/shi042508.htm| work=Metropolitan News-Enterprise | publisher= Metropolitan News Company| date=25 April 2008 | accessdate=6 May 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\n[[File:Barkhad Abdi at LFCC Awards.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|Barkhad Abdi portrayed Muse in ''[[Captain Phillips (film)|Captain Phillips]]'']]\nMuse was portrayed by Somali actor [[Barkhad Abdi]] in the 2013 film ''[[Captain Phillips (film)|Captain Phillips]]'', a dramatization of the events in 2009, also starring [[Tom Hanks]] as the [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|titular character]]. The film received a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and Abdi was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his portrayal of Muse.\n\n==Additional attacks==\nIn 2010, Muse was charged in connection with two additional attacks on international shipping.<ref>{{cite news |title= Somali Man Is Charged in 2 More Ship Hijackings |first= Benjamin |last= Weiser |authorlink= Benjamin Weiser |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= 12 January 2010 |quote=  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Maersk Alabama suspect charged in two other piracy incidents |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/01/12/maersk.alabama.charges/index.html |date=12 January 2010 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> The indictment does not name the two vessels involved, hijacked in March and April 2009. However, they are likely to include the 700-ton fishing vessel ''[[FV Win Far 161|Win Far 161]]'', which was used as a [[mother ship]] in other attacks, including the ''Maersk Alabama'' hijacking.<ref>{{cite news |first= Chiang|last= Huang-chih|authorlink= |url= http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2009/09/07/2003452966 |format= |agency= |newspaper= [[Taipei Times]]|publisher= |location= |date= 7 September 2009 |title= Does MOFA care about 'Win Far'?  |quote= }}</ref><ref name=BBC8510938>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8510938.stm |title=Somali pirates free Taiwanese fishing boat |publisher=BBC News |date=11 February 2010 |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> Two of the ''Win Far 161's'' crew, one sailor from mainland China and the other from Indonesia, died of illness.<ref name=xiamen10786>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/news10786.html |title=Hijacked Taiwan fishing boat Win Far 161 escorted home |publisher=Whats On Xiamen |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053755/http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/news10786.html |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nMuse was tried in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Somali 'pirate' to be tried in US |journal=BBC |date=17 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8003936.stm |accessdate=17 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420040535/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8003936.stm |archivedate=20 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThere was some confusion as to his age.  According to the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', he was at the time 17 to 19 years old.<ref name=NYDailyNews/> Muse was to stand trial in New York because of the local [[FBI]] office's expertise in handling cases where major crimes were perpetrated against Americans in Africa, such as the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] in [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]]. [[CBC News]] also reported that U.S. authorities had considered transferring him to authorities in Kenya per international agreement to prosecute pirate suspects.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/><ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-16\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/captured-somalian-pirate-to-face-trial-in-u-s-1.777443| title=Captured Somalian pirate to face trial in U.S.| date=16 April 2009| quote=If Wal-i-Musi is under 18, federal prosecutors would have to take a number of additional steps to justify charging him in federal court.| publisher=[[CBC News]]\n|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fworld%2Fstory%2F2009%2F04%2F16%2Fphillips-kenya-pirates016.html&date=2009-04-20\n|archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhen initially captured, U.S. officials reported Muse as being 16 to 20 years old, and that his name was Abduhl Wali-i-Musi. U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] asserted that all four pirate suspects were between the ages of 17 and 19. On 20 April 2009, [[CBC News]] reported that U.S. officials indicated that investigators had confirmed Muse was over 18, which removed additional steps that would be required to prosecute him had it been determined that he was a minor.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/>\n\nMuse's mother, Adar Abdurahman Hassan, stated in a telephone interview with the [[Associated Press]] that U.S. authorities had both his name and age wrong.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/> She indicated that he was only 16 years old and that his name was Abdi Wali Abdulqadir Muse. In an interview with the [[BBC Somali]] service, Muse's mother also appealed to the U.S. government and president to free her son,<ref name=bbcsomali>{{cite news|title=Mother of boy accused of piracy speaks to the BBC |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2009/04/090421_somali_mother_nh.shtml |work=[[BBC World Service]] |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422152813/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2009/04/090421_somali_mother_nh.shtml |archivedate=22 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> asserting that Muse had been lured into pirate activity by wealthy unnamed criminals.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/>\n\nIn a court ruling on 21 April 2009, U.S. Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck decided Muse was not under 18 and that he could be [[Trial as an adult|tried as an adult]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Indictment 21 April 2009 |url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/nyregion/22pirate_Complaint.pdf |accessdate=29 April 2009 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=October 2016}} Muse was then brought to New York to face trial on charges including piracy under the [[law of nations]], [[Conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]] to seize a ship by force, conspiracy to commit [[hostage]]-taking, and firearms related charges, carrying a potential of up to four life sentences.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Somali 'pirate' appears in court |journal=BBC |date=21 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8010131.stm |accessdate=21 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422011742/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8010131.stm |archivedate=22 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The charge of piracy has a mandatory life sentence (18 USC 1651),<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/1651 \"USC: Title 18: Part I: Chapter 81: \u00a7 165118 USC \u00a7 1651 - Piracy under law of nations\"]. Legal Information Institute. [[Cornell University Law School]].</ref> and there is no parole in U.S. federal prisons.\n\nOn 19 May 2009, a federal [[grand jury]] in New York returned a ten-count indictment against Muse.<ref name=\"MusiIndictment\">{{cite news|url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html |title=Indictment (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse) |date=19 May 2009 |publisher=FindLaw |accessdate=19 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626070734/http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html |archivedate=26 June 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMuse pleaded guilty to the hijacking, kidnapping and hostage-taking charges on 18 May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title= Somali man pleads guilty to seizing US merchant ship|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/us_and_canada/10124279.stm |agency= BBC News |date= 18 May 2010|quote=  }}</ref> Charges of [[piracy]] and possession of a [[machine gun]] were dropped in exchange for the guilty plea.<ref name=\"Nsmpgithocs\">{{cite news |title=Somali Man Pleads Guilty in 2009 Hijacking of Cargo Ship |first= Ray|last= Rivera|authorlink=Ray Rivera |author2= Benjamin Weiser|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/19/nyregion/19pirate.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|date= 18 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2011, Muse was sentenced to 33 years and 9 months in federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Somali pirate sentenced to 33 years in US prison |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-12486129 |agency=BBC News |date=16 February 2011 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217030938/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-12486129 |archivedate=17 February 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Imprisonment==\nMuse is now incarcerated at the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Edgefield]] in [[South Carolina]]. His release date is April 13, 2038.<ref name=\"BOP\"/>  Previously, he was incarcerated at the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Terre Haute|Federal Correctional Complex]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], [[Indiana]].\n\nMuse worked as a prison orderly, although his wage was garnished to pay the restitution he owes for the hijacking as well as a court fee. He said he spent his free time in prison watching TV, reading and writing. In 2016, he acquired a [[GED]]. He spent some time in solitary confinement for being \"disruptive\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/smiling-somali-pirate-says-jailers-have-ruined-his-grin | title='Smiling' Somali Pirate Says Jailers Have Ruined His Grin | date=30 June 2018 | first=Justin | last=Rohrlich | publisher=The Daily Beast | accessdate=1 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4346433/united-states-v-muse/ Muse's criminal docket] on [[Court Listener]].\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html Indictment] (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse), 19 May 2009 [[FindLaw]]\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse42109cmp.html Criminal Complaint] (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse), 21 April 2009 [[FindLaw]]\n{{pirates}}\n{{Piracy in Somalia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muse, Abduwali Abdukhadir}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Galkayo]]\n[[Category:21st-century Somalian people]]\n[[Category:Hijackers]]\n[[Category:Kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Somalian pirates]]\n[[Category:21st-century pirates]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:Sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Somalian criminals]]\n[[Category:Somalian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Abduwali Muse\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name       = Abduwali Muse\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1990}}<ref name=\"BOP\" />\n| birth_place        = [[Galkayo]], [[Somalia]]\n| alias              = Abdulwali Abdukhad Muse,<ref name=\"BOP\" /> Abdul Wali Muse, Wal-i-Musi\n| allegiance         = \n| motive             = \n| charge             = [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|''Maersk Alabama'' hijacking]]\n| conviction         = \n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated on [[piracy]] charges. Sentenced to 33 years and 9 months imprisonment. Currently located at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Edgefield]], to be released April 13, 2038.\n| occupation      = Pirate\n| parents            = Adar Abdurahman Hassan\n}}\n'''Abduwali Muse''' ({{lang-so|Cabdiweli Cabdiqaadir Muuse}}; {{IPA-so|\u0295\u0251bd\u026aw\u025bli \u0295\u0251bd\u026aq\u0251\u02d0d\u026ar mu\u02d0s\u025b|pron}}; {{Audio|En-us-Abdiwali Abdukhadir Muse from Somalia pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg|English pronunciation}}) is a convicted [[Somali people|Somali]] [[pirate]]. He is the sole survivor of four pirates who [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|hijacked]] the {{ship|MV|Maersk Alabama}} in April 2009 and then held Captain [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|Richard Phillips]] for ransom.<ref name=NYDailyNews>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/04/17/2009-04-17_free_and_frisky_sailor_william_rios_held_by_somali_pirates_rejoins_wife_in_harle.html| quote=It was not known when he will be brought to stand trial in New York, chosen because the local FBI office has a history of handling cases in Africa involving major crimes against Americans. His tribe is the Hawiye in the Darood clan. The suspect, believed to be 17 to 19 years old, could face life in prison if convicted.| title=Free and frisky: Maersk Alabama sailor William Rios, held by Somali pirates, rejoins wife in Harlem| date=17 April 2009|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nydailynews.com%2Fnews%2F2009%2F04%2F17%2F2009-04-17_free_and_frisky_sailor_william_rios_held_by_somali_pirates_rejoins_wife_in_harle.html&date=2009-04-20|archivedate=20 April 2009| first1=Erica| last1=Pearson}}</ref> On 16 February 2011, Muse was sentenced to over 33 years in U.S. federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Somali pirate gets over 33 years in prison |first=Tom |last=Hays |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110216/ap_on_re_us/us_piracy_suspect |agency=AAP |date=16 February 2011 |publisher=News.Yahoo.com |accessdate=30 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218083517/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110216/ap_on_re_us/us_piracy_suspect |archivedate=18 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMuse was born in [[Galkayo]], a [[divided city]] in [[Somalia]]. The US Federal Bureau of Prisons states he was born in 1990,<ref name=\"BOP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=70636-054 |title=Inmate Locator |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] |accessdate=22 February 2014 | quote = ABDULWALI ABDUKHAD MUSE, AGE: 24, Register Number: 70636-054}}</ref> while his mother states he was born in 1992,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pirate mother's Obama mercy plea |journal=BBC |date=20 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8008835.stm |accessdate=20 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421011850/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8008835.stm |archivedate=21 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/somalian-pirate-suspect-arrives-in-new-york-to-be-tried-in-u-s-court-1.777441 | title=Somali pirate being flown to New York to be tried in U.S. federal court| date=20 April 2009| publisher=[[CBC News]]| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fworld%2Fstory%2F2009%2F04%2F20%2Fus-somaliapirate.html&date=2009-04-20| archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref> and his father states he was born in 1993.<ref name=\"NbcNews2009-04-20\">{{cite news| url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Captured-Somali-Pirate-En-Route-to-NY-for-Trial.html| title=Captured Somali Pirate Due in NY Court Tomorrow| date=20 April 2009| author=Jonathon Dienst, Victoria Cavaliere| publisher=[[NBC News]]\n|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nbcnewyork.com%2Fnews%2Flocal%2FCaptured-Somali-Pirate-En-Route-to-NY-for-Trial.html&date=2009-04-20| archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/nyregion/22pirate.html| title=Pirate Suspect Charged as Adult in New York| date=21 April 2009| author=Benjamin Weiser|work=[[The New York Times]]| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002203050/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/nyregion/22pirate.html| url-status=live| archivedate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WashingtonPost2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html\n|title=Somali Charged With Piracy in Attack on U.S. Ship| date=22 April 2009| first1=Colleen | last1=Long | first2=Larry | last2=Neumeister|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114044624/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html| url-status=live\n|archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe grew up in poverty often without food or clothes. At a young age he was kicked in the face by Mickey Mouse and lost two of his front teeth. By the age of 12, he was living alone and initially worked as an assistant to taxi drivers before working as a cook for fishermen. He was married in 2008 but could not afford to establish a home for himself and his wife.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-15068088 |title = Somali pirates face hard time in US prison|work = BBC News|date = 3 October 2011|last1 = Nasaw|first1 = Daniel}}</ref>\n\nAt a hearing to determine Muse's age, Assistant [[United States Attorney]] Brendan McGuire said to U.S. Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck, that Muse had told Americans he was variously 16, 18, 19 and 26 years old.\n\nMuse is short in stature&mdash;Colleen Long and Larry Neumeister, writing for the [[Associated Press]], reported that Muse was, \"only five foot two inches (157&nbsp;cm) tall.\"<ref name=\"AssociatedPress2009-04-21\">{{cite news| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5izUbtx1o15cqD9GcYDcuI16mUxQQD97N62H00| title=Pirate comes to NY, world away from home in Africa| date=21 April 2009| author=Colleen Long, Larry Neumeister\n |agency=Associated Press| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Fhostednews%2Fap%2Farticle%2FALeqM5izUbtx1o15cqD9GcYDcuI16mUxQQD97N62H00&date=2009-04-22| archivedate=22 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Attack on the ''Maersk Alabama''==\n{{further|Maersk Alabama hijacking}}\nAccording to his indictment, Muse was the first of the four men who boarded the ''[[Maersk Alabama]]''. During the attack, he was stabbed in the hand by a sailor. The crew attacked and held Muse hostage while [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|Richard Phillips]] offered him and the pirates money to leave the ''Alabama'' safely on the ship's lifeboat. However Muse's fellow pirates forced Phillips into the lifeboat before the ''Alabama'' crew could release Muse. All four pirates escaped the ship, with Phillips held hostage inside the lifeboat. A day later the ''[[USS Bainbridge (DDG-96)|USS Bainbridge]]'' intercepted the lifeboat and navy officers negotiated with the armed pirates for hours and agreed to take Muse on board the ''Bainbridge'' to \"meet\" with elders from his clan to negotiate the release of Phillips. After Muse had been taken on board, the three remaining pirates were shot dead simultaneously before Muse was charged and taken into American custody. Muse was thought to be the first person to be charged with [[piracy]] in an American court in more than 100 years,<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|first=Ed |last=Pilkington |title=Somali teen faces first US piracy charges in over a century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/21/somali-pirate-trial-new-york |work=The Guardian |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2009 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424055601/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/21/somali-pirate-trial-new-york |archivedate=24 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> when courts ruled in 1885 that the [[Ambrose Light (ship)|''Ambrose Light'']] was not a pirate vessel. A more recent case, 2008's ''[[United States v. Shi]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=United States v. Shi |url=http://www.dailycasereport.com/index.php?q=open_pdf/3596 |accessdate=25 April 2009}}</ref> which was quoted in his indictment, involves murder and a crew member taking over a ship and holding a hostage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ellis |first=Steven M. | title= Ninth Circuit Court Upholds Chinese Man's Piracy Conviction | url= http://www.metnews.com/articles/2008/shi042508.htm| work=Metropolitan News-Enterprise | publisher= Metropolitan News Company| date=25 April 2008 | accessdate=6 May 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\n[[File:Barkhad Abdi at LFCC Awards.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|Barkhad Abdi portrayed Muse in ''[[Captain Phillips (film)|Captain Phillips]]'']]\nMuse was portrayed by Somali actor [[Barkhad Abdi]] in the 2013 film ''[[Captain Phillips (film)|Captain Phillips]]'', a dramatization of the events in 2009, also starring [[Tom Hanks]] as the [[Richard Phillips (merchant mariner)|titular character]]. The film received a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and Abdi was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his portrayal of Muse.\n\n==Additional attacks==\nIn 2010, Muse was charged in connection with two additional attacks on international shipping.<ref>{{cite news |title= Somali Man Is Charged in 2 More Ship Hijackings |first= Benjamin |last= Weiser |authorlink= Benjamin Weiser |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/13/nyregion/13pirate.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= 12 January 2010 |quote=  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Maersk Alabama suspect charged in two other piracy incidents |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/01/12/maersk.alabama.charges/index.html |date=12 January 2010 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> The indictment does not name the two vessels involved, hijacked in March and April 2009. However, they are likely to include the 700-ton fishing vessel ''[[FV Win Far 161|Win Far 161]]'', which was used as a [[mother ship]] in other attacks, including the ''Maersk Alabama'' hijacking.<ref>{{cite news |first= Chiang|last= Huang-chih|authorlink= |url= http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2009/09/07/2003452966 |format= |agency= |newspaper= [[Taipei Times]]|publisher= |location= |date= 7 September 2009 |title= Does MOFA care about 'Win Far'?  |quote= }}</ref><ref name=BBC8510938>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8510938.stm |title=Somali pirates free Taiwanese fishing boat |publisher=BBC News |date=11 February 2010 |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> Two of the ''Win Far 161's'' crew, one sailor from mainland China and the other from Indonesia, died of illness.<ref name=xiamen10786>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/news10786.html |title=Hijacked Taiwan fishing boat Win Far 161 escorted home |publisher=Whats On Xiamen |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053755/http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/news10786.html |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nMuse was tried in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Somali 'pirate' to be tried in US |journal=BBC |date=17 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8003936.stm |accessdate=17 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420040535/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8003936.stm |archivedate=20 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThere was some confusion as to his age.  According to the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', he was at the time 17 to 19 years old.<ref name=NYDailyNews/> Muse was to stand trial in New York because of the local [[FBI]] office's expertise in handling cases where major crimes were perpetrated against Americans in Africa, such as the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] in [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]]. [[CBC News]] also reported that U.S. authorities had considered transferring him to authorities in Kenya per international agreement to prosecute pirate suspects.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/><ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-16\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/captured-somalian-pirate-to-face-trial-in-u-s-1.777443| title=Captured Somalian pirate to face trial in U.S.| date=16 April 2009| quote=If Wal-i-Musi is under 18, federal prosecutors would have to take a number of additional steps to justify charging him in federal court.| publisher=[[CBC News]]\n|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fworld%2Fstory%2F2009%2F04%2F16%2Fphillips-kenya-pirates016.html&date=2009-04-20\n|archivedate=20 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhen initially captured, U.S. officials reported Muse as being 16 to 20 years old, and that his name was Abduhl Wali-i-Musi. U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] asserted that all four pirate suspects were between the ages of 17 and 19. On 20 April 2009, [[CBC News]] reported that U.S. officials indicated that investigators had confirmed Muse was over 18, which removed additional steps that would be required to prosecute him had it been determined that he was a minor.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/>\n\nMuse's mother, Adar Abdurahman Hassan, stated in a telephone interview with the [[Associated Press]] that U.S. authorities had both his name and age wrong.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/> She indicated that he was only 16 years old and that his name was Abdi Wali Abdulqadir Muse. In an interview with the [[BBC Somali]] service, Muse's mother also appealed to the U.S. government and president to free her son,<ref name=bbcsomali>{{cite news|title=Mother of boy accused of piracy speaks to the BBC |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2009/04/090421_somali_mother_nh.shtml |work=[[BBC World Service]] |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=21 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422152813/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2009/04/090421_somali_mother_nh.shtml |archivedate=22 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> asserting that Muse had been lured into pirate activity by wealthy unnamed criminals.<ref name=\"Cbc2009-04-20\"/>\n\nIn a court ruling on 21 April 2009, U.S. Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck decided Muse was not under 18 and that he could be [[Trial as an adult|tried as an adult]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Indictment 21 April 2009 |url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/nyregion/22pirate_Complaint.pdf |accessdate=29 April 2009 | work=The New York Times}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=October 2016}} Muse was then brought to New York to face trial on charges including piracy under the [[law of nations]], [[Conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]] to seize a ship by force, conspiracy to commit [[hostage]]-taking, and firearms related charges, carrying a potential of up to four life sentences.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Somali 'pirate' appears in court |journal=BBC |date=21 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8010131.stm |accessdate=21 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422011742/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8010131.stm |archivedate=22 April 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The charge of piracy has a mandatory life sentence (18 USC 1651),<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/1651 \"USC: Title 18: Part I: Chapter 81: \u00a7 165118 USC \u00a7 1651 - Piracy under law of nations\"]. Legal Information Institute. [[Cornell University Law School]].</ref> and there is no parole in U.S. federal prisons.\n\nOn 19 May 2009, a federal [[grand jury]] in New York returned a ten-count indictment against Muse.<ref name=\"MusiIndictment\">{{cite news|url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html |title=Indictment (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse) |date=19 May 2009 |publisher=FindLaw |accessdate=19 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626070734/http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html |archivedate=26 June 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nMuse pleaded guilty to the hijacking, kidnapping and hostage-taking charges on 18 May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title= Somali man pleads guilty to seizing US merchant ship|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/us_and_canada/10124279.stm |agency= BBC News |date= 18 May 2010|quote=  }}</ref> Charges of [[piracy]] and possession of a [[machine gun]] were dropped in exchange for the guilty plea.<ref name=\"Nsmpgithocs\">{{cite news |title=Somali Man Pleads Guilty in 2009 Hijacking of Cargo Ship |first= Ray|last= Rivera|authorlink=Ray Rivera |author2= Benjamin Weiser|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/19/nyregion/19pirate.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|date= 18 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2011, Muse was sentenced to 33 years and 9 months in federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Somali pirate sentenced to 33 years in US prison |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-12486129 |agency=BBC News |date=16 February 2011 |accessdate=16 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217030938/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-12486129 |archivedate=17 February 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Imprisonment==\nMuse is now incarcerated at the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Edgefield]] in [[South Carolina]]. His release date is April 13, 2038.<ref name=\"BOP\"/>  Previously, he was incarcerated at the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Terre Haute|Federal Correctional Complex]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], [[Indiana]].\n\nMuse worked as a prison orderly, although his wage was garnished to pay the restitution he owes for the hijacking as well as a court fee. He said he spent his free time in prison watching TV, reading and writing. In 2016, he acquired a [[GED]]. He spent some time in solitary confinement for being \"disruptive\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/smiling-somali-pirate-says-jailers-have-ruined-his-grin | title='Smiling' Somali Pirate Says Jailers Have Ruined His Grin | date=30 June 2018 | first=Justin | last=Rohrlich | publisher=The Daily Beast | accessdate=1 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/4346433/united-states-v-muse/ Muse's criminal docket] on [[Court Listener]].\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse51909ind.html Indictment] (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse), 19 May 2009 [[FindLaw]]\n* [http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/piracy/usmuse42109cmp.html Criminal Complaint] (U.S. v. Abduwali Abdukhadir Muse), 21 April 2009 [[FindLaw]]\n{{pirates}}\n{{Piracy in Somalia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muse, Abduwali Abdukhadir}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Galkayo]]\n[[Category:21st-century Somalian people]]\n[[Category:Hijackers]]\n[[Category:Kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Somalian pirates]]\n[[Category:21st-century pirates]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:Sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Somalian criminals]]\n[[Category:Somalian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "name_user": "LilMagnusVert", "label": "safe", "comment": "a camel", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abduwali_Muse"}
{"title_page": "Peter Walker (landscape architect)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Peter Walker}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Nichols Prize Luncheon Peter Walker, Laureate 2012 (8467494497).jpg|thumb|Peter Walker at the [[Urban Institute]] 2012]]\n'''Peter Walker''' is an American [[landscape architect]] and the founder of PWP Landscape Architecture.\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Walker<ref name =\"Peter Walker Bio\">[http://tclf.org/pioneer/peter-walker The Cultural Landscape Foundation], The Cultural Landscape Foundation.</ref><ref name=\"Peter Walker is a visionary in Urban Development\">[http://dirt.asla.org/2013/02/20/peter-walker-is-a-visionary-in-urban-development/ ASLA- The Dirt], ASLA- The Dirt Bio.</ref>  grew up in California and attended the [[University of California, Berkeley]].  Walker started out studying Journalism but quickly changed his field.  He received his Bachelor of Science in [[Landscape Architecture]] in 1955, and did his graduate studies at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] where he studied under [[Stanley Hart White|Stanley White]].<ref name=\"Stanley White Publications\">[http://archives.library.illinois.edu/archon/?p=collections/controlcard&id=1293 \"Stanley White Papers, 1925-1977 | University of Illinois Archives.\" Stanley White Papers, 1925-1977 | University of Illinois Archives. N.p., n.d. Web. 09 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n\nWalker attended the [[Harvard University]] [[Graduate School of Design]], where he received his masters in Landscape Architecture in 1957, and won the school's [[Jacob Weidenmann]] Prize<ref name=\"Jacob Weidenmann\">[http://tclf.org/pioneer/jacob-weidenmann \"The Cultural Landscape Foundation.\" Jacob Weidenmann. The Cultural Landscape Foundation, n.d. Web. 09 Feb. 2015.]</ref><ref name=\"Weidenman Prize\">[http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/#/academic-programs/landscape-architecture/fellowships-prizes-travel-programs.html Weidenman Prize] Prize Description</ref> that year.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Career==\nAt Harvard, Walker had been deeply influenced by his professor, [[Hideo Sasaki]]. After graduating, he worked for Sasaki. Shortly thereafter, they both went into partnership to form Sasaki Walker Associates in 1957.\n\nPeter Walker and Sasaki went their separate ways in 1983, and Walker went into partnership with landscape architect [[Martha Schwartz]].<ref name=\"Mozingo 255\">Mozingo, ''Pastoral Capitalism'', Notes p. 255</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s Walker formed Peter Walker and Partners.<ref name=\"Mozingo 255\" /> In a 1993 review, Walker was one of four landscape architects named as representative of the new generation.<ref>Treib, ''Modern Landscape Architecture: A Critical Review'', page viii</ref> The company developed into an interdisciplinary firm that employs around thirty to forty landscape architects. The company has received many awards<ref>http://www.pwpla.com/frm_awards.php</ref> and co-designed the [[World Trade Center Memorial]] in New York with architect [[Michael Arad]].<ref>[http://www.dezeen.com/2011/08/22/dezeen-screen-911-memorial-by-michael-arad-and-peter-walker/ \"9/11 memorial by Michael Arad and Peter Walker\"], dezeen Magazine, August 22, 2011.</ref>\n\nWalker designed the garden for the [[Nasher Sculpture Center]]. In 2013 he was involved in a public argument with the architect of a neighboring building, [[Museum Tower (Dallas)|Museum Tower]], because the glare from the glass was damaging the vegetation. Walker described it as \"public desecration\".<ref>\n{{cite news |last=Granberry |first=Michael |coauthors= |title=Landscape architect Peter Walker, who designed the Nasher garden, strongly denounces Museum Tower and its ownership|work=GuideLive arts blog |publisher=The Dallas Morning News |date=June 13, 2013 |url=http://artsblog.dallasnews.com/2013/06/landscape-architect-peter-walker-who-designed-the-nasher-strongly-denounces-museum-tower-and-its-ownership.html/ |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPeter Walker is also a co-author of ''Invisible Gardens'', which touches on the modernist movement in America and the comparison of other landscapes to those in Europe.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}  The book discusses influential landscape architects, such as Hideo Sasaki.\n\nIn 2006, he was invited to join the judging panel for an international design competition for the new [[Gardens by the Bay]] in [[Singapore]].\n\n==Awards==\n*2004 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects Medal|ASLA Medal]],<ref name=\"ASLA Medal 2004\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2004/medals/walker.htm The ASLA Medal 2004: Peter E. Walker, FASLA], ASLA.org</ref> the highest medal of the [[American Society of Landscape Architects]].\n*2004 - [[American Society of Landscape Architects|ASLA]] Honor Award: Design, Nasher Sculpture Center<ref name= \"ASLA Honor Award for Nasher Sculpture\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2004/04winners/entry332.html \"ASLA.org.\" \u00a9 ASLA.org. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2005 - The ''Geoffrey Jellicoe Gold Medal''<ref name=\"IFLA Highest Honor\">[http://americas.iflaonline.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=44&Itemid=66 \"Landscape Awards.\" Landscape Awards. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> from the International Federation of Landscape Architects''.<ref name=\"IFLA Award Geoffrey Jollicoe Gold Metal Award\">[http://iflaonline.org/awards/sir-geoffrey-jellicoe-award/past-sgja-awardees/2005-sgja/ \"2005 SGJA \u00b7 IFLA World.\" 2005 SGJA \u00b7 IFLA World. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2008 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects|ASLA]] Landmark Award for Tanner Fountain at [[Harvard University]], Cambridge, Massachusetts<ref name=\"The Landmark Award from the ASLA\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2008/08winners/312.html \"ASLA 2008 Professional Awards.\" ASLA 2008 Professional Awards. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2010 - [[Green building on college campuses#Stanford University: Knight Management Center|Knight Management Center: Stanford GSB]] awarded Green Project of the Year by the Silicon Valley/San Jose Business Journal<ref name=\"Green Project of the Year\">[http://www.gsb.stanford.edu/newsroom/school-news/new-home-stanford-gsb-honored-sustainability \"New Home of Stanford GSB Honored for Sustainability.\" Stanford Graduate School of Business. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2012 - The [[Urban Land Institute#Awards and competitions|J.C. Nichols Prize]] Winner for Visionaries in Urban Development from the [[Urban Land Institute]]<ref name=\"Urban Land Institute\">[http://uli.org/press-release/world-renowned-landscape-architect-peter-walker-is-the-2012-laureate-of-the-uli-j-c-nichols-prize-for-visionaries-in-urban-development/ 2012 Nichols Prize Winner], Peter Walker wins 2012 ULI J.C. Nicols Prize.</ref>\n*2012 - Peter Walker & PWP Landscape Architecture awarded the Liberty Award by the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"LMCC Liberty Award\">[http://lmcc.net/event/the-downtown-dinner-2012/ \"Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.\" Lower Manhattan Cultural Council. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2012 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects Medal|ASLA Medal]] Recipient.<ref name=\"ASLA Medal 2012\">[http://asla.org/AwardRecipient.aspx?id=35680 \"2012 ASLA Design Medal Recipient | Asla.org.\" 2012 ASLA Design Medal Recipient | Asla.org. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2014 - The James Daniel Bybee Prize Recipient.<ref name=\"Bybee Prize Recipient 2014\">[http://www.buildingstoneinstitute.org/about-us/programs/tucker-design-awards/bybee-prize/?wppa-album=4&wppa-cover=0&wppa-occur=1&wppa-photo=149 \"Frasca-1.jpg.\" Building Stone Institute RSS. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n\n==Notable projects==\n\n=== Australia ===\n* [[Barangaroo, New South Wales|Barangaroo Headlands Park]] in Sydney, New South Wales\n\n=== Europe ===\n* [[Novartis | Novartis Headquarters]] in Basel, Switzerland\n* [[Sony Center|The Sony Center]] in Berlin, Germany\n* [[Munich Airport#Munich Airport Center|Munich Airport - Hotel Kempinski]] in Munich, Germany\n\n=== United States ===\n* [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]] in New York, New York\n* [[San Francisco Transbay Terminal|Transbay Terminal]] in San Francisco, California\n* [[Jamison Square]] in Portland, Oregon\n* [[Pixar |Pixar Headquarters]] in Emeryville, California\n* [[Constitution Gardens]] in Washington, D.C. (won competition for partial redesign in 2012)<ref>[http://www.archdaily.com/231625/winners-announced-for-the-national-mall-redesign-competition/ \"Winners announced for the National Mall Redesign Competition\"], ''Archdaily'', May 3, 2012.</ref>\n* [[Glenstone]] in Potomac, Maryland<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/glenstone-museum-expansion|title=Tour the New $200 Million Expansion of One of America's Most Important\u2014and Unknown\u2014Museums|last=Mendelsohn|first=Meredith|date=2018-09-27|work=Architectural Digest|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927194035/https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/glenstone-museum-expansion|archive-date=2018-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Newport Beach Civic Center and Park]] in Newport Beach, California\n\n=== Asia ===\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]] in Singapore\n* [[Marina Bay Sands]] in Singapore\n* [[Ciudad de Victoria]] in Bocaue, Philippines\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* Walker, Peter, and Leah Levy. ''Peter Walker: Minimalist Gardens. Washington,'' DC: Spacemaker, 1997. Print.<ref name=\"City Review\">[http://www.thecityreview.com/walker.htm Horsley, Carter B. \"Books: Minimalist Gardens by Peter Walker.\" Books: Minimalist Gardens by Peter Walker. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n* ''Invisible Gardens: The Search for Modernism in the American Landscape''. Walker, Peter, and Melanie Simo. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT-Press, 1998. Print.Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT-Press, 1998.<ref name=\"Good Reads Synopsis of Invisible Gardens\">[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/191379.Invisible_Gardens \"Invisible Gardens.\" Goodreads. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n* ''Peter Walker and Partners: Defining the Craft.'' Walker, Peter. San Rafael, CA: ORO Editions, 2005. Print.<ref name=\"Good Reads synopsis of Defining the Craft\">[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/936531.Peter_Walker_Partners \"Peter Walker Partners.\" ''Goodreads''. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.], Peter Walker and Partners: Defining the Craft.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Citation|last1=Mozingo |first1=Louise A. |title=Pastoral Capitalism: A History of Suburban Corporate Landscapes |place= |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |year=2011|isbn=978-0-262-01543-1 }}\n* {{Citation|last1=Treib |first1=Marc |title=Modern Landscape Architecture: A Critical Review |place= |publisher=Mit Press |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-262-70051-1 }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pwpla.com Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American landscape architects]]\n[[Category:American landscape and garden designers]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley College of Environmental Design alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Peter Walker}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Nichols Prize Luncheon Peter Walker, Laureate 2012 (8467494497).jpg|thumb|Peter Walker at the [[Urban Institute]] 2012]]\n'''Peter Walker''' is an American [[landscape architect]] and the founder of PWP Landscape Architecture.\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Walker<ref name =\"Peter Walker Bio\">[http://tclf.org/pioneer/peter-walker The Cultural Landscape Foundation], The Cultural Landscape Foundation.</ref><ref name=\"Peter Walker is a visionary in Urban Development\">[http://dirt.asla.org/2013/02/20/peter-walker-is-a-visionary-in-urban-development/ ASLA- The Dirt], ASLA- The Dirt Bio.</ref>  grew up in California and attended the [[University of California, Berkeley]].  Walker started out studying Journalism but quickly changed his field.  He received his Bachelor of Science in [[Landscape Architecture]] in 1955, and did his graduate studies at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] where he studied under [[Stanley Hart White|Stanley White]].<ref name=\"Stanley White Publications\">[http://archives.library.illinois.edu/archon/?p=collections/controlcard&id=1293 \"Stanley White Papers, 1925-1977 | University of Illinois Archives.\" Stanley White Papers, 1925-1977 | University of Illinois Archives. N.p., n.d. Web. 09 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n\nWalker attended the [[Harvard University]] [[Graduate School of Design]], where he received his masters in Landscape Architecture in 1957, and won the school's [[Jacob Weidenmann]] Prize<ref name=\"Jacob Weidenmann\">[http://tclf.org/pioneer/jacob-weidenmann \"The Cultural Landscape Foundation.\" Jacob Weidenmann. The Cultural Landscape Foundation, n.d. Web. 09 Feb. 2015.]</ref><ref name=\"Weidenman Prize\">[http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/#/academic-programs/landscape-architecture/fellowships-prizes-travel-programs.html Weidenman Prize] Prize Description</ref> that year.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Career==\nAt Harvard, Walker had been deeply influenced by his professor, [[Hideo Sasaki]]. After graduating, he worked for Sasaki. Shortly thereafter, they both went into partnership to form Sasaki Walker Associates in 1957.\n\nPeter Walker and Sasaki went their separate ways in 1983, and Walker went into partnership with landscape architect [[Martha Schwartz]].<ref name=\"Mozingo 255\">Mozingo, ''Pastoral Capitalism'', Notes p. 255</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s Walker formed Peter Walker and Partners.<ref name=\"Mozingo 255\" /> In a 1993 review, Walker was one of four landscape architects named as representative of the new generation.<ref>Treib, ''Modern Landscape Architecture: A Critical Review'', page viii</ref> The company developed into an interdisciplinary firm that employs around thirty to forty landscape architects. The company has received many awards<ref>http://www.pwpla.com/frm_awards.php</ref> and co-designed the [[World Trade Center Memorial]] in New York with architect [[Michael Arad]].<ref>[http://www.dezeen.com/2011/08/22/dezeen-screen-911-memorial-by-michael-arad-and-peter-walker/ \"9/11 memorial by Michael Arad and Peter Walker\"], dezeen Magazine, August 22, 2011.</ref>\n\nWalker designed the garden for the [[Nasher Sculpture Center]]. In 2013 he was involved in a public argument with the architect of a neighboring building, [[Museum Tower (Dallas)|Museum Tower]], because the glare from the glass was damaging the vegetation. Walker described it as \"public desecration\".<ref>\n{{cite news |last=Granberry |first=Michael |coauthors= |title=Landscape architect Peter Walker, who designed the Nasher garden, strongly denounces Museum Tower and its ownership|work=GuideLive arts blog |publisher=The Dallas Morning News |date=June 13, 2013 |url=http://artsblog.dallasnews.com/2013/06/landscape-architect-peter-walker-who-designed-the-nasher-strongly-denounces-museum-tower-and-its-ownership.html/ |accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPeter Walker is also a co-author of ''Invisible Gardens'', which touches on the modernist movement in America and the comparison of other landscapes to those in Europe.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}  The book discusses influential landscape architects, such as Hideo Sasaki.\n\nIn 2006, he was invited to join the judging panel for an international design competition for the new [[Gardens by the Bay]] in [[Singapore]].\n\n==Awards==\n*2004 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects Medal|ASLA Medal]],<ref name=\"ASLA Medal 2004\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2004/medals/walker.htm The ASLA Medal 2004: Peter E. Walker, FASLA], ASLA.org</ref> the highest medal of the [[American Society of Landscape Architects]].\n*2004 - [[American Society of Landscape Architects|ASLA]] Honor Award: Design, Nasher Sculpture Center<ref name= \"ASLA Honor Award for Nasher Sculpture\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2004/04winners/entry332.html \"ASLA.org.\" \u00a9 ASLA.org. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2005 - The ''Geoffrey Jellicoe Gold Medal''<ref name=\"IFLA Highest Honor\">[http://americas.iflaonline.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=44&Itemid=66 \"Landscape Awards.\" Landscape Awards. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> from the International Federation of Landscape Architects''.<ref name=\"IFLA Award Geoffrey Jollicoe Gold Metal Award\">[http://iflaonline.org/awards/sir-geoffrey-jellicoe-award/past-sgja-awardees/2005-sgja/ \"2005 SGJA \u00b7 IFLA World.\" 2005 SGJA \u00b7 IFLA World. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2008 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects|ASLA]] Landmark Award for Tanner Fountain at [[Harvard University]], Cambridge, Massachusetts<ref name=\"The Landmark Award from the ASLA\">[http://www.asla.org/awards/2008/08winners/312.html \"ASLA 2008 Professional Awards.\" ASLA 2008 Professional Awards. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2010 - [[Green building on college campuses#Stanford University: Knight Management Center|Knight Management Center: Stanford GSB]] awarded Green Project of the Year by the Silicon Valley/San Jose Business Journal<ref name=\"Green Project of the Year\">[http://www.gsb.stanford.edu/newsroom/school-news/new-home-stanford-gsb-honored-sustainability \"New Home of Stanford GSB Honored for Sustainability.\" Stanford Graduate School of Business. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2012 - The [[Urban Land Institute#Awards and competitions|J.C. Nichols Prize]] Winner for Visionaries in Urban Development from the [[Urban Land Institute]]<ref name=\"Urban Land Institute\">[http://uli.org/press-release/world-renowned-landscape-architect-peter-walker-is-the-2012-laureate-of-the-uli-j-c-nichols-prize-for-visionaries-in-urban-development/ 2012 Nichols Prize Winner], Peter Walker wins 2012 ULI J.C. Nicols Prize.</ref>\n*2012 - Peter Walker & PWP Landscape Architecture awarded the Liberty Award by the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"LMCC Liberty Award\">[http://lmcc.net/event/the-downtown-dinner-2012/ \"Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.\" Lower Manhattan Cultural Council. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2012 - The [[American Society of Landscape Architects Medal|ASLA Medal]] Recipient.<ref name=\"ASLA Medal 2012\">[http://asla.org/AwardRecipient.aspx?id=35680 \"2012 ASLA Design Medal Recipient | Asla.org.\" 2012 ASLA Design Medal Recipient | Asla.org. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n*2014 - The James Daniel Bybee Prize Recipient.<ref name=\"Bybee Prize Recipient 2014\">[http://www.buildingstoneinstitute.org/about-us/programs/tucker-design-awards/bybee-prize/?wppa-album=4&wppa-cover=0&wppa-occur=1&wppa-photo=149 \"Frasca-1.jpg.\" Building Stone Institute RSS. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n\n==Notable projects==\n\n=== Australia ===\n* [[Barangaroo, New South Wales|Barangaroo Headlands Park]] in Sydney, New South Wales\n\n=== Europe ===\n* [[Novartis | Novartis Headquarters]] in Basel, Switzerland\n* [[Sony Center|The Sony Center]] in Berlin, Germany\n* [[Munich Airport#Munich Airport Center|Munich Airport - Hotel Kempinski]] in Munich, Germany\n\n=== United States ===\n* [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum|National 911 Memorial]] in New York, New York\n* [[San Francisco Transbay Terminal|Transbay Terminal]] in San Francisco, California\n* [[Jamison Square]] in Portland, Oregon\n* [[Pixar |Pixar Headquarters]] in Emeryville, California\n* [[Constitution Gardens]] in Washington, D.C. (won competition for partial redesign in 2012)<ref>[http://www.archdaily.com/231625/winners-announced-for-the-national-mall-redesign-competition/ \"Winners announced for the National Mall Redesign Competition\"], ''Archdaily'', May 3, 2012.</ref>\n* [[Glenstone]] in Potomac, Maryland<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/glenstone-museum-expansion|title=Tour the New $200 Million Expansion of One of America's Most Important\u2014and Unknown\u2014Museums|last=Mendelsohn|first=Meredith|date=2018-09-27|work=Architectural Digest|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927194035/https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/glenstone-museum-expansion|archive-date=2018-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Newport Beach Civic Center and Park]] in Newport Beach, California\n\n=== Asia ===\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]] in Singapore\n* [[Marina Bay Sands]] in Singapore\n* [[Ciudad de Victoria]] in Bocaue, Philippines\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* Walker, Peter, and Leah Levy. ''Peter Walker: Minimalist Gardens. Washington,'' DC: Spacemaker, 1997. Print.<ref name=\"City Review\">[http://www.thecityreview.com/walker.htm Horsley, Carter B. \"Books: Minimalist Gardens by Peter Walker.\" Books: Minimalist Gardens by Peter Walker. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n* ''Invisible Gardens: The Search for Modernism in the American Landscape''. Walker, Peter, and Melanie Simo. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT-Press, 1998. Print.Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT-Press, 1998.<ref name=\"Good Reads Synopsis of Invisible Gardens\">[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/191379.Invisible_Gardens \"Invisible Gardens.\" Goodreads. N.p., n.d. Web. 02 Feb. 2015.]</ref>\n* ''Peter Walker and Partners: Defining the Craft.'' Walker, Peter. San Rafael, CA: ORO Editions, 2005. Print.<ref name=\"Good Reads synopsis of Defining the Craft\">[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/936531.Peter_Walker_Par